  "local_port": 56612,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm 4 years into my H1B, my GC is not yet started. If I apply GC through consulting company, do I need to join this company before filing I-140/I485?",
  "response": "To apply for a Green Card (GC) through employment with a consulting company while on an H-1B visa, certain steps and considerations come into play regarding compliance with U.S. immigration laws:\n\n1. **Job Offer Requirement**: Generally, you must have a legitimate job offer from the consulting company when filing for the Green Card. This typically means that you should either be employed or have a formal employment agreement in place.\n\n2. **Joining Before Filing**: While technically it is possible to file an I-140 and I-485 without being employed at the company (if you have a valid job offer and meet the requirements), it is generally recommended to join the company before submitting these applications. This is because the employer must show the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) that you are indeed planning to work for them and that they have a position available for you.\n\n3. **Labor Certification (PERM)**: The process often begins with a labor certification (PERM), which demonstrates that there are no qualified U.S. workers available for the position. Your employment status can impact this process.\n\n4. **Maintaining H-1B Status**: If you are still under an H-1B from another employer, transitioning to a new employer (in this case, the consulting company) may involve filing a new H-1B or amending your current one, as well as navigating your current employment situation properly.\n\n5. **Risks**: If you file without joining the company first, there may be risks involved related to your intentions and your current immigration status. USCIS looks for evidence of a bona fide employment relationship.\n\n6. **Consult an Immigration Attorney**: Given the complex nature of immigration laws and the nuances of your specific situation, it is highly advisable to consult with an immigration attorney. They can provide guidance tailored to your circumstances, ensuring compliance with all legal requirements.\n\nIn summary, while it may be possible to file the I-140/I-485 without having joined the consulting company first, it is safer and more common to be employed by the sponsoring company when submitting your application.",
